Methods

The RCS includes 3-items from the Veterans Affairs Saint Louis University Mental Status (SLUMS) exam: recall of 5 words, a clock drawing test, and the ability to remember a story and convert the fact that Chicago is in Illinois (Figure 1). RCS scores range from 0=worst to 10=best, including memory (5 points), clock drawing (4 points; 2 points for hour markers, 2 points for time), and story (1 point). The CDT plus recall consists of clock drawing (2 points) and recall of 3 words (3 points).
Figure 1 Rapid Cognitive Screen (RCS)

In our first study the ability of the RCS to discriminate between normal cognition, MCI, and dementia on the DSMIV; to predict nursing home placement and mortality; and to perform as well or better than the CDT plus recall were evaluated using our database (18). DSM-IV criteria were used to make the diagnosis of mild neurocognitive disorder or dementia. The sample included N=702 participants ages 65-92 from the Saint Louis Veterans Affairs Medical Center hospitals recruited in 2003. Dementia was present in 12% (n=82) of participants and 26% (n=180) participants had MCI. All participants were males (100%). Participant follow-up to evaluate the association of RCS scores with nursing home placement and mortality up to 7.5 years after completing the RCS included N=533/702 participants. Participants (n=169/702) were lost to follow-up due to a change in primary care provider, incorrect contact information or inactive electronic medical record. There were no differences in age, gender, or education for participants lost to follow-up, compared to those with valid follow-up data for nursing home placement and mortality.
In a second study we examined the ability of the RCS to detect dementia and MCI in an outpatient setting. The sample included N=168 participants ages 60-90 from the Saint Louis University Geriatric Medicine and Geriatric Psychiatry outpatient clinics in 2013. There were 44% (n=74) participants with dementia and 36% (n=61) participants with MCI. The sample was 62% (n=104) female. African Americans were 42% (n=71) of the participants and Caucasians were 55% (n=92).

Statistics Data were analyzed using IBM SPSS Statistics, version 22 (Somers, NY) and SAS, version 9.2 (SAS Institute, Inc., Cary, NC) for ROC contrasts. Descriptive statistics are reported as means + standard deviations (SD) or percentages. Scale total scores for the RCS (0-10) and CDT plus recall (0-5) were used for ROC curves for MCI and dementia. Using a standard approach, sensitivity and specificity were calculated for the RCS and CDT plus recall. ROC contrasts were computed to compare the total area under the curve (AUC) of the screening tests (RCS vs. CDT plus recall) for MCI and for dementia on the DSM-IV. Logistic regression was used to investigate the

