In study one, the RCS predicted dementia (AUC=0.98, 95% CI: 0.95-1.00) and MCI (AUC=0.86, 95% CI: 0.830.89) on the DSM-IV. RCS optimal cutoff scores were ≤ 5 for dementia (sensitivity=0.89, specificity=0.94) and ≤ 7 for MCI (sensitivity=0.87, specificity=0.70). The CDT plus recall also predicted dementia (AUC=0.92, 95% CI: 0.890.96) and MCI (AUC=0.66, 95% CI: 0.61-0.70) on the DSM-IV. CDT plus recall optimal cutoff scores were ≤ 2 for dementia (sensitivity=0.87, specificity=0.85) and ≤ 3 for MCI (sensitivity=0.62, specificity=0.62). The RCS and CDT plus recall ROC curves for dementia based on the DSM-IV are displayed in Figure 2a. A ROC contrast comparing the AUCs for dementia shows that the RCS (AUC=0.98) performed better than the CDT plus recall (AUC=0.92) (p < .01). The RCS and CDT plus recall ROC curves for MCI on the DSM-IV are displayed in Figure 2b. A ROC contrast comparing the AUCs for MCI shows that the RCS (AUC=0.86) was superior to the CDT plus recall (AUC=0.66) (p<.001). Higher RCS scores (0-10) were protective against nursing home placement (OR per point on the RCS=0.85, 95% CI: 0.73-0.98) and mortality (OR per point on the RCS=0.84, 95% CI: 0.77-0.91) up to 7.5 years later.

