Discussion
Our objective was to assess the performance of a much needed brief screening tool for cognitive impairment. The RCS exhibited construct validity to screen for dementia and MCI in both studies. Study one showed that the 3-item RCS and the 2-item CDT plus recall have high sensitivity and specificity for detecting dementia on the DSM-IV, and study two showed that the RCS also has very good sensitivity and specificity for the detection of dementia on the SLUMS exam. The optimal scores for dementia on the RCS were ≤ 5 in both studies, and on the CDT plus recall were ≤ 2. The RCS exhibited good sensitive and specificity for detecting MCI on the DSM-IV (study one) and SLUMS (study two) with optimal scores of ≤ 7. The CDT plus recall exhibited only modest sensitivity and specificity for the detection of MCI on the DSM-IV with optimal scores of ≤ 3. ROC contrasts for the AUC showed that the RCS is a better predictor overall of dementia and MCI on the DSM-IV with

