the largest difference observed for MCI. The RCS predictive validity for institutionalization and mortality after 7.5 years was also investigated in study one. Persons without RCS scores in the MCI and/or dementia range were less likely to be institutionalized or die over 7.5 years.
Figure 2d RCS ROC Curve for MCI on the SLUMS Exam
The RCS and the CDT plus recall are both very brief screening instruments that can be administered in < 3 minutes in a busy clinical setting. The CDT alone has previously been shown to be a good measure to screening for dementia (23). This study provides preliminary evidence that the RCS may also be an effective measure to screen for dementia. The RCS may be a better tool than the CDT plus recall for detecting MCI based on the results of our study; the CDT alone has not been studied as a measure to detect MCI. Previous studies have shown mixed results regarding the utility of the Mini-Cog to detect MCI (24, 25). More evidence and further study of the RCS as a screening tool for cognitive impairment are warranted based on the studies reported herein.
The RCS is valid, very brief (< 3 minutes), easy to administer and score, and has no copyright. This study provides preliminary evidence that the RCS may be a useful screening instrument for the detection of cognitive impairment in a busy clinical setting.
